<BaseLayout
  title="How Streaming Payouts Work | How Much Music"
  description="A clear explanation of how streaming services turn streams into music revenue."
  type="article"
>
  <section>
    <p class="eyebrow">Explainer</p>
    <h1>How streaming payouts work</h1>
    <p>
      There is no single universal payout per stream. Services pool subscription and ad revenue,
      keep their platform share, then allocate the rest through rights holders based on territory,
      plan type, and the contract stack behind the recording.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What matters most</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Premium streams usually monetize better than ad-supported streams.</li>
      <li>Geography matters because subscription prices and ad yields differ by market.</li>
      <li>The artist rarely receives the full platform payout after label, distributor, and publishing splits.</li>
      <li>One viral month can distort attention, but durable playlist and catalog replay usually matter more for yearly value.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why there is no fixed per-stream rate</h2>
    <p>
      A stream is an allocation event, not a fixed coin drop. Services collect money from
      subscriptions and advertising, divide it across rights holders, and then the rights-holder
      contracts decide what reaches labels, distributors, publishers, writers, artists, and estates.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is why a defensible estimate should avoid pretending that every stream is worth one
      universal number. A high-income market, paid subscription stream, and favorable rights
      structure can behave very differently from a low-yield ad-supported stream.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The payout path in plain English</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li><strong>Listener activity:</strong> Plays happen across paid subscriptions, ad-supported sessions, videos, and territory-specific products.</li>
      <li><strong>Platform pool:</strong> Each service calculates rights-holder payments from revenue pools, not from a universal public rate.</li>
      <li><strong>Rights-holder layer:</strong> The master recording and composition are paid through different rights paths.</li>
      <li><strong>Contract layer:</strong> Labels, distributors, publishers, writers, producers, artists, and estates divide money according to deal terms that are usually private.</li>
      <li><strong>Artist-side estimate:</strong> A conservative range is more useful than presenting gross revenue as take-home income.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why ranges are more useful</h2>
    <p>
      A precise public payout figure is usually not available. The defensible approach is to model a
      range and then explain what assumptions sit behind the artist-side estimate.
    </p>
    <p>
      The range is most useful when paired with context: whether the song is evergreen,
      seasonal, sync-friendly, label-heavy, writer-controlled, or mostly dependent on current
      streaming momentum.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How to use this on song pages</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Read streaming as one revenue lane, not the whole business.</li>
      <li>Compare songs by annual range and midpoint, not only by lifetime stream count.</li>
      <li>Check whether the page separates gross revenue from artist-side take-home.</li>
      <li>Use platform links as listening context, not audited royalty evidence.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
